WEBVTT

00:01.460 --> 00:04.421
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.421 --> 00:07.132
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:07.132 --> 00:10.093
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:10.093 --> 00:15.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.807 --> 00:17.893
- I'm Mark Sperry.

00:17.893 --> 00:19.686
I'm a full-time blacksmith
at Colonial Williamsburg.

00:19.686 --> 00:22.397
<i>It's certainly not</i>
<i>a neat occupation.</i>

00:22.397 --> 00:25.234
<i>It requires me coming</i>
<i>in the house stinky and dirty</i>

00:25.234 --> 00:27.027
all the time,

00:27.027 --> 00:29.696
which probably is
frustrating for the family.

00:29.696 --> 00:31.740
<i>- My name is Nicholas Downing.</i>

00:31.740 --> 00:33.784
<i>I first started bladesmithing</i>
<i>in middle school.</i>

00:33.784 --> 00:35.786
I ended up building
a really primitive forge

00:35.786 --> 00:37.871
<i>in my parents' backyard.</i>

00:37.871 --> 00:39.540
<i>I almost set the house</i>
<i>on fire a couple of time.</i>

00:39.540 --> 00:42.626
The flames were about
like yea, so, yeah.

00:42.626 --> 00:44.044
Whoops.

00:44.044 --> 00:45.587
<i>- My name is John Dickinson.</i>

00:45.587 --> 00:47.798
I'm retired from
the Forest Service.

00:47.798 --> 00:49.716
<i>I spent 28 years, 6 months,</i>

00:49.716 --> 00:52.761
<i>and 14 days doing fire</i>
<i>and law enforcement.</i>

00:52.761 --> 00:55.264
Normally, when
I'm making a blade,

00:55.264 --> 00:58.100
I take a number of breaks
over several days,

00:58.100 --> 01:01.603
<i>but I have pretty good stamina</i>
<i>because fighting a fire,</i>

01:01.603 --> 01:03.814
you have to work all day
and all night.

01:03.814 --> 01:05.774
<i>- My name's Garrin Bucco.</i>

01:05.774 --> 01:06.900
I'm about as far as you can get
from

01:06.900 --> 01:08.610
bladesmithing professionally.

01:08.610 --> 01:10.571
<i>I'm a dental assistant.</i>

01:10.571 --> 01:13.323
<i>I'm also a writer;</i>
<i>I'm working on a novel</i>

01:13.323 --> 01:15.492
<i>that'll actually be</i>
<i>finished pretty soon.</i>

01:15.492 --> 01:17.286
It has nothing to do
with bladesmithing at all.

01:17.286 --> 01:19.621
It's completely unrelated.

01:19.621 --> 01:22.332
- Bladesmiths, welcome
to The Forge.

01:22.332 --> 01:23.959
You're here for three timed

01:23.959 --> 01:25.627
rounds of bladesmithing
competition

01:25.627 --> 01:28.255
designed to test every aspect
of your capabilities

01:28.255 --> 01:30.340
in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:30.340 --> 01:32.342
who determines which of you
is our next "Forged in Fire"

01:32.342 --> 01:35.637
champion and the recipient
of that $10,000 check.

01:35.637 --> 01:37.764
Let's go ahead
and meet your judges now.

01:37.764 --> 01:40.475
ABS Master Smith, J. Neilson.

01:40.475 --> 01:43.520
Historic Weapons Re-creation
Specialist, David Baker.

01:43.520 --> 01:47.274
Edged Weapons Specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:47.274 --> 01:49.234
All right, gents.

01:49.234 --> 01:51.820
Today you'll be forging
your blades from these.

01:51.820 --> 01:55.699
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:55.699 --> 01:58.368
We've got sledgehammers,
we have crowbars,

01:58.368 --> 02:00.454
and we have fire hooks.

02:00.454 --> 02:03.832
<i>- I'm seeing tools that I've</i>
<i>used in fire situations</i>

02:03.832 --> 02:05.542
<i>and I'm thinking,</i>

02:05.542 --> 02:06.626
"Man, they knew
a fireman was coming,

02:06.626 --> 02:08.378
and they're picking on me."

02:08.378 --> 02:13.008
- Each by itself
is a capable rescue tool.

02:13.008 --> 02:15.594
However, in the background
that I come from,

02:15.594 --> 02:17.137
anything that you carry
into the field

02:17.137 --> 02:19.473
should have multiple uses.

02:19.473 --> 02:23.810
So we want you to use one or
more of these single-use tools

02:23.810 --> 02:28.523
and combine them into your own
version of a multipurpose tool.

02:28.523 --> 02:30.359
Your took should have
a cutting edge

02:30.359 --> 02:32.653
<i>that falls between 4</i>
<i>and 10 inches in length.</i>

02:32.653 --> 02:36.239
<i>It must also have</i>
<i>the prying teeth of a crowbar,</i>

02:36.239 --> 02:39.868
<i>and it must have a hammerhead</i>
<i>anyplace on the tool.</i>

02:39.868 --> 02:43.080
<i>- I came in here expecting</i>
<i>to make a knife and that's it,</i>

02:43.080 --> 02:45.999
<i>but here they want me</i>
<i>to make much more than a knife</i>

02:45.999 --> 02:48.960
and that's gonna be
really awesome.

02:48.960 --> 02:51.088
- Keep in mind that after
the second round,

02:51.088 --> 02:53.423
your weapons will be tested
for strength and durability

02:53.423 --> 02:55.801
in a pry, hammer and chop,

02:55.801 --> 02:58.887
and for sharpness
in a fire hose slice.

02:58.887 --> 03:00.681
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

03:00.681 --> 03:03.350
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:03.350 --> 03:05.018
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:05.018 --> 03:08.522
Your ten-minute
design window starts now.

03:08.522 --> 03:11.191
What kind of forms are we
expecting to see out there?

03:11.191 --> 03:13.485
- Well, you could see
machete-type blades,

03:13.485 --> 03:15.112
you could see axes.

03:15.112 --> 03:17.364
There's a lot of variety.

03:17.364 --> 03:19.282
<i>- What's gonna be hard about</i>
<i>this challenge in particular</i>

03:19.282 --> 03:21.952
is going to be the design.

03:21.952 --> 03:25.080
<i>The easiest, most sensical way</i>
<i>for me to get the hammer</i>

03:25.080 --> 03:26.790
<i>on there is to put it</i>
<i>on the pommel,</i>

03:26.790 --> 03:28.500
<i>and you're gonna have</i>
<i>a knife blade</i>

03:28.500 --> 03:30.293
<i>right where that usually is,</i>

03:30.293 --> 03:32.462
<i>and then the pry bar</i>
<i>is going right out</i>

03:32.462 --> 03:34.548
<i>at the end after the blade.</i>

03:34.548 --> 03:38.051
I started "bladesmithing"
when I was 12.

03:38.051 --> 03:39.469
<i>We had these aluminum</i>
<i>straps from,</i>

03:39.469 --> 03:41.388
<i>like, curtains or something,</i>

03:41.388 --> 03:42.889
<i>and I just dug a hole,</i>
<i>started a wood fire</i>

03:42.889 --> 03:44.850
and started "forging" aluminum,

03:44.850 --> 03:46.768
<i>and at any kind</i>
<i>of temperature,</i>

03:46.768 --> 03:48.270
<i>aluminum just falls apart.</i>

03:48.270 --> 03:50.355
I switched to steel
pretty quickly

03:50.355 --> 03:51.606
because I realized
that's what you're actually

03:51.606 --> 03:52.566
supposed to use.

03:52.566 --> 03:54.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:54.401 --> 03:57.070
- I'm choosing to put
the pry bar section

03:57.070 --> 03:58.822
<i>out on the very end,</i>

03:58.822 --> 04:01.575
<i>the hammer on the spine</i>
<i>of the knife,</i>

04:01.575 --> 04:05.036
<i>and then opposite of that</i>
<i>having the cutting edge.</i>

04:05.036 --> 04:07.080
<i>I'm currently working on</i>
<i>getting my journeyman's stamp</i>

04:07.080 --> 04:08.999
with the ABS.

04:08.999 --> 04:11.126
<i>I'm about halfway</i>
<i>through the process.</i>

04:11.126 --> 04:13.044
I'm very antsy, very nervous

04:13.044 --> 04:18.049
<i>about whether or not</i>
<i>I can pull it off.</i>

04:18.049 --> 04:21.803
- The judges are asking for
an awful lot for one tool.

04:21.803 --> 04:25.849
<i>The design I'm making</i>
<i>has a axe-type blade.</i>

04:25.849 --> 04:28.560
<i>One part can be offset</i>
<i>to make the hammerhead</i>

04:28.560 --> 04:30.270
<i>and the other part drawn out</i>

04:30.270 --> 04:33.523
and split on the end
to make a pry bar.

04:33.523 --> 04:36.359
If I win that $10,000, well,

04:36.359 --> 04:40.405
my girlfriend says
she's got plans.

04:40.405 --> 04:42.908
[laughs]

04:42.908 --> 04:45.702
- I'm feeling nervous.
I'm not gonna lie.

04:45.702 --> 04:48.538
<i>I'm thinking that I'm gonna put</i>
<i>the crowbar teeth in the front,</i>

04:48.538 --> 04:50.415
<i>have an edge down the side,</i>

04:50.415 --> 04:52.000
<i>and then have a big,</i>
<i>heavy hammer pommel.</i>

04:52.000 --> 04:53.794
<i>I'm competing</i>
<i>on "Forged in Fire"</i>

04:53.794 --> 04:55.754
to test my skills against
some really good smiths,

04:55.754 --> 04:58.048
<i>and also for</i>
<i>my girlfriend's dad.</i>

04:58.048 --> 04:59.883
<i>Every time he sees me</i>
<i>he asks me</i>

04:59.883 --> 05:01.134
<i>when I'm gonna be</i>
<i>on "Forged in Fire."</i>

05:01.134 --> 05:03.094
Chuck, I'm here.

05:03.094 --> 05:04.805
- Your ten-minute
design window is closed.

05:04.805 --> 05:08.642
Your three-hour forge time
starts right now.

05:08.642 --> 05:11.311
- Oh, [bleep].
- So these crowbars

05:11.311 --> 05:13.480
are tensile steel.

05:13.480 --> 05:16.274
Now, the fireman's hook,
is that hardenable steel,

05:16.274 --> 05:18.109
or is it just the head?

05:18.109 --> 05:20.111
- It's about the same steel
as the pry bar,

05:20.111 --> 05:21.822
and then the hammerheads,

05:21.822 --> 05:23.323
we've seen those used
in here before,

05:23.323 --> 05:24.991
so, I mean,
all of those are good steels.

05:24.991 --> 05:27.327
- Look at that,
Garrin's using the pry tool.

05:27.327 --> 05:28.453
- Even though some of
these tools

05:28.453 --> 05:30.789
have pry teeth on them,

05:30.789 --> 05:34.167
we want to see the smiths
make new pry teeth.

05:34.167 --> 05:36.711
- Oh, yeah, that's same thing
with the hammerheads.

05:36.711 --> 05:38.964
<i>- Fitting the three tools</i>
<i>onto this one thing</i>

05:38.964 --> 05:41.716
in three hours
is gonna be the challenge.

05:41.716 --> 05:45.387
<i>The best steel out there</i>
<i>that I can see is the crowbar</i>

05:45.387 --> 05:46.972
<i>because it's fairly close</i>

05:46.972 --> 05:48.515
to the final dimensions
of the stock

05:48.515 --> 05:50.267
I'd like to be using anyway.

05:50.267 --> 05:51.643
<i>I have my plan.</i>

05:51.643 --> 05:53.270
<i>I'm gonna start upsetting</i>

05:53.270 --> 05:56.565
the end of the crowbar
into a hammer.

05:56.565 --> 05:58.692
- Oh, nice.

05:58.692 --> 06:00.402
- Upsetting the head of the
pry bar into a hammerhead.

06:00.402 --> 06:01.903
So what he's doing
is heating that end,

06:01.903 --> 06:04.155
smashing it
so he's mushrooming it out

06:04.155 --> 06:07.033
so it's swelling that end up.
That'll make his hammerhead.

06:07.033 --> 06:08.618
- I know it's gonna be
the hardest part

06:08.618 --> 06:10.579
of the whole process,

06:10.579 --> 06:14.875
but as long as I take my time,
breathe, I'll be okay.

06:14.875 --> 06:18.753
- So Garrin's got a piece
of crowbar. So does Nicholas.

06:18.753 --> 06:20.714
- I zeroed in on the crowbar

06:20.714 --> 06:22.966
<i>because the crowbar's</i>
<i>fairly straightforward.</i>

06:22.966 --> 06:26.261
- Nicholas' design is nearly
identical to Garrin's.

06:26.261 --> 06:28.138
- They'll have their hammer
heads on the pommels

06:28.138 --> 06:29.848
so anybody out there in TV land

06:29.848 --> 06:31.808
who wants to know
the problem here,

06:31.808 --> 06:33.852
go in your shop, take the
handle off one of your hammers

06:33.852 --> 06:35.520
and try holding it

06:35.520 --> 06:37.689
and hammering a nail
in through steel.

06:37.689 --> 06:39.649
You don't get a lot of momentum
swinging into it.

06:39.649 --> 06:41.484
It's gonna be awkward.

06:41.484 --> 06:43.653
If I miss the nail,
I'm gonna tear my hand up.

06:43.653 --> 06:45.947
That's gonna be a lot of fun.

06:45.947 --> 06:48.867
<i>- I know that I have enough</i>
<i>steel in it to make a knife.</i>

06:48.867 --> 06:50.744
What I need to know

06:50.744 --> 06:53.663
is can I upset it enough
to make a hammerhead?

06:53.663 --> 06:55.749
- Takes forever to heat up.

06:55.749 --> 06:57.250
- It's a big [bleep] piece
of steel, dude.

06:57.250 --> 06:58.209
- I know.

06:58.209 --> 07:00.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:00.211 --> 07:01.921
<i>I didn't think</i>
<i>the crowbar was big enough</i>

07:01.921 --> 07:04.424
for the design
that I came up with,

07:04.424 --> 07:06.092
<i>so I chose the sledgehammer</i>

07:06.092 --> 07:08.470
because it has the mass
that I needed.

07:08.470 --> 07:10.388
- These are 12-pound
sledgehammers.

07:10.388 --> 07:13.475
That's the weight of the head,
not the entire system.

07:13.475 --> 07:15.935
You don't need 12 pounds
of steel to make something

07:15.935 --> 07:18.772
that should weigh less
than 2 pounds.

07:18.772 --> 07:21.816
- I'm getting frustrated
because I'm not accomplishing

07:21.816 --> 07:24.277
much work at this point.

07:24.277 --> 07:26.029
<i>I just need to get</i>
<i>the hammer drawed out</i>

07:26.029 --> 07:28.239
and then I can cut off

07:28.239 --> 07:33.119
what I need and work
with a much smaller piece.

07:33.119 --> 07:35.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:35.580 --> 07:37.749
- The main source of the steel
for this tool

07:37.749 --> 07:40.126
is gonna be
the sledgehammer head.

07:40.126 --> 07:42.462
<i>It has sufficient metal in it</i>

07:42.462 --> 07:45.256
<i>to draw out into the various</i>
<i>components of the multi-tool.</i>

07:45.256 --> 07:46.883
- That's way more steel

07:46.883 --> 07:48.551
than he's ever
gonna need right there.

07:48.551 --> 07:50.970
Just carrying that's
gonna be exhausting.

07:50.970 --> 07:52.931
- I'm also going to cut the
tubular handle

07:52.931 --> 07:54.933
<i>of the fire hook,</i>

07:54.933 --> 07:57.519
and it will be inserted
into the eye of the hammer.

07:57.519 --> 07:58.645
- Does John know that
he doesn't have to use

07:58.645 --> 08:00.605
all the steel?

08:00.605 --> 08:02.691
<i>- This hammerhead</i>
<i>is a big chunk of iron,</i>

08:02.691 --> 08:06.945
and if nothing else, it's gonna
wear me out just holding it up.

08:06.945 --> 08:08.780
- One hour has elapsed.

08:08.780 --> 08:11.324
That means you have
just two hours remaining

08:11.324 --> 08:14.953
to finish those
multipurpose tools.

08:14.953 --> 08:17.956
- Within the first hour I've
got my basic shape established.

08:17.956 --> 08:20.250
<i>I've roughed out</i>
<i>in my pommel area.</i>

08:20.250 --> 08:22.168
<i>I'm feeling pretty good.</i>

08:22.168 --> 08:25.922
- Nicholas' knife is shaped
just like him, skinny.

08:25.922 --> 08:27.757
- Lean.

08:27.757 --> 08:29.300
- Now, I need to start
to define the area

08:29.300 --> 08:31.386
that's gonna be the pry bar.

08:31.386 --> 08:33.972
<i>There's this funny irony</i>
<i>in that because a lot of times</i>

08:33.972 --> 08:36.516
when you take a square bar
and you squish it down,

08:36.516 --> 08:39.436
you end up with
a little crack, and here,

08:39.436 --> 08:41.604
I'm actually trying to do that.

08:41.604 --> 08:45.108
- We got Nicholas chiseling
out his fork.

08:45.108 --> 08:47.068
That's gonna
take a long time.

08:47.068 --> 08:50.447
- Despite the fact that I work
with fire and hammers,

08:50.447 --> 08:52.282
I'm a pretty sensitive guy.

08:52.282 --> 08:56.244
I like art
and cooking and cats.

08:56.244 --> 08:58.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:58.413 --> 09:02.959
- I'm feeling pretty good.
I'm feeling great, actually.

09:02.959 --> 09:05.503
The tool is starting
to take shape.

09:05.503 --> 09:06.963
Eh, yeah.

09:06.963 --> 09:08.757
<i>Now I'm gonna make the pry.</i>

09:08.757 --> 09:11.342
The big thing is not
to get it too thin.

09:11.342 --> 09:13.511
<i>If they pry that nail,</i>

09:13.511 --> 09:16.890
that tooth closer to the edge
of the blade could snap off.

09:16.890 --> 09:18.641
- Garrin is gonna
cut his teeth in

09:18.641 --> 09:21.019
- It's an easier way
to get there.

09:21.019 --> 09:22.771
<i>- I think I'm representing</i>

09:22.771 --> 09:24.773
the dental assistants
of America right now

09:24.773 --> 09:26.649
<i>because I am around little,</i>

09:26.649 --> 09:29.110
<i>tiny spinning rotary tools all</i>
<i>day.</i>

09:29.110 --> 09:32.197
I'm in my element here.

09:32.197 --> 09:35.325
<i>- It took longer to reduce</i>
<i>the size of that material</i>

09:35.325 --> 09:37.035
<i>than it should have taken.</i>

09:37.035 --> 09:40.288
Now I have to start
to isolate material

09:40.288 --> 09:42.999
that I need for the hammer.

09:42.999 --> 09:44.501
- Mark's is the only design

09:44.501 --> 09:46.503
that really is
making sense to me.

09:46.503 --> 09:48.213
- He still got lot of work to
do on that hammerhead, though.

09:48.213 --> 09:50.131
- I agree.

09:50.131 --> 09:52.634
<i>- I feel like</i>
<i>I'm making good progress,</i>

09:52.634 --> 09:56.805
but I still got
more material to shape.

09:56.805 --> 10:00.016
I wanted to come and compete
here on "Forged in Fire,"

10:00.016 --> 10:02.477
<i>because I enjoy</i>
<i>watching the show,</i>

10:02.477 --> 10:05.438
and I didn't feel right
sitting in my living room

10:05.438 --> 10:07.565
<i>making comments at the TV.</i>

10:07.565 --> 10:10.902
"Why are you doing that?
Oh, my God, don't do that."

10:10.902 --> 10:15.323
So I put my hat in the ring
to try it for myself.

10:15.323 --> 10:18.576
<i>- The drawing out of the blade</i>
<i>is actually going fairly well.</i>

10:18.576 --> 10:21.996
It's actually starting
to look like a cutting blade.

10:21.996 --> 10:25.416
I take I over to the forge
to heat it up again.

10:25.416 --> 10:26.501
- John's starting to have
a hard time getting

10:26.501 --> 10:28.336
that axe head in the forge.

10:28.336 --> 10:31.506
- Yeah.
<i>- Um, okay,</i>

10:31.506 --> 10:33.424
I'm gonna have to
change strategy

10:33.424 --> 10:36.928
a little bit
and chop some of that off.

10:36.928 --> 10:38.680
- I like John's design,

10:38.680 --> 10:41.474
but, man, it really
needs to go on a diet.

10:41.474 --> 10:45.311
<i>- My blade is designed</i>
<i>to knock down doors.</i>

10:45.311 --> 10:47.313
- Two hours has elapsed.

10:47.313 --> 10:50.608
That leaves you only 60 minutes
to finish your work.

10:50.608 --> 10:52.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:52.360 --> 10:53.528
- I really got to get the ball
rolling

10:53.528 --> 10:55.321
on my heat-treating process.

10:55.321 --> 10:58.032
- I always hate seeing people
with a narrow tip

10:58.032 --> 10:59.826
on their blade

10:59.826 --> 11:01.828
put the blade in tip
first for heat treating.

11:01.828 --> 11:04.247
You're gonna overheat it.
You get a more brittle tip.

11:04.247 --> 11:06.875
So now, we've got Nicholas
who's got two narrow tips

11:06.875 --> 11:09.210
that are heating up
like match flames.

11:09.210 --> 11:12.672
<i>- I'm trying to get the blade</i>
<i>heated as evenly as I can.</i>

11:12.672 --> 11:14.549
If the teeth end up
getting a little too hot,

11:14.549 --> 11:16.259
I risk cracking them.

11:16.259 --> 11:17.886
<i>If the blade</i>
<i>is heated unevenly,</i>

11:17.886 --> 11:20.096
I risk warping it
or cracking it.

11:20.096 --> 11:22.974
It's really a make-or-break-it
moment.

11:22.974 --> 11:24.851
- Nicholas is in the quench.

11:24.851 --> 11:26.603
- There was no big woof.

11:26.603 --> 11:29.397
I didn't get a ball
of fire in my face.

11:29.397 --> 11:30.982
<i>It skates right across.</i>

11:30.982 --> 11:34.861
I got a hard blade.
I'm very pleased.

11:34.861 --> 11:37.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:37.113 --> 11:38.823
<i>- I know a good heat treat,</i>
<i>especially for the pry</i>

11:38.823 --> 11:40.658
and especially for the chop,

11:40.658 --> 11:42.577
is gonna be really important,

11:42.577 --> 11:45.538
<i>so I want to make sure</i>
<i>my oil is preheated</i>

11:45.538 --> 11:47.790
<i>because the temperature</i>
<i>of the oil</i>

11:47.790 --> 11:49.542
and the temperature of the
blade

11:49.542 --> 11:51.628
is what's gonna make
this a good heat treat.

11:51.628 --> 11:54.547
- What happens if you overheat
the oil, J., is that possible?

11:54.547 --> 11:56.049
- Oh, yeah.
You can overheat the oil,

11:56.049 --> 11:58.176
then your blade
won't cool as rapidly.

11:58.176 --> 12:00.428
- And when your blade doesn't
cool as rapidly, what happens?

12:00.428 --> 12:02.180
- You got a better chance
of blades cracking

12:02.180 --> 12:04.182
or just not hardening up.

12:04.182 --> 12:06.184
You could have soft spots
and hard spots in the blade

12:06.184 --> 12:09.687
instead of even hardness all
down the length of the blade.

12:09.687 --> 12:12.065
- Garrin just quenched.

12:12.065 --> 12:14.525
- It seems like it was
a good quench.

12:14.525 --> 12:16.361
[bleep].

12:16.361 --> 12:17.862
But it doesn't quite skate
over the surface

12:17.862 --> 12:19.656
<i>the way it's supposed to.</i>

12:19.656 --> 12:22.116
So that means I don't think
I have a blade

12:22.116 --> 12:24.160
that's perfectly hard.

12:24.160 --> 12:26.496
<i>I put so much effort</i>
<i>into this heat treat,</i>

12:26.496 --> 12:28.289
the simplest thing should be
getting a hard blade

12:28.289 --> 12:30.250
<i>at this point.</i>

12:30.250 --> 12:33.378
I don't want to, but I need
to do this again.

12:33.378 --> 12:35.338
[speaks Spanish]

12:35.338 --> 12:37.382
In the second quench,
I know it has to be right,

12:37.382 --> 12:41.261
or this thing is going to get
wrecked on the stress test,

12:41.261 --> 12:44.062
<i>or worse, I might not make it</i>
<i>through to the next round.</i>

12:47.433 --> 12:49.686
- Quench over there, Garrin.

12:49.686 --> 12:52.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:52.230 --> 12:54.232
- The moment of truth.

12:54.232 --> 12:56.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:56.442 --> 12:58.111
I think it's good.

12:58.111 --> 12:59.737
<i>I can feel it skate.</i>

12:59.737 --> 13:00.822
It's feeling good, so
at this point,

13:00.822 --> 13:02.448
I take a deep breath.

13:02.448 --> 13:03.866
<i>I've got a hard blade.</i>

13:03.866 --> 13:05.827
Now, from here on out,

13:05.827 --> 13:09.289
it's just fine tuning
and getting it looking good.

13:09.289 --> 13:11.416
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:11.416 --> 13:14.043
- I'm in the home stretch,
and I'm feeling the shape

13:14.043 --> 13:17.380
of my blade fulfills
the needs of the challenge

13:17.380 --> 13:19.465
<i>I wish it was</i>
<i>a little bit prettier,</i>

13:19.465 --> 13:22.176
but it's more about function

13:22.176 --> 13:26.222
<i>than aesthetics.</i>

13:26.222 --> 13:27.640
- So Mark just quenched
his blade.

13:27.640 --> 13:28.766
- Yep.

13:28.766 --> 13:31.269
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.269 --> 13:33.062
- [bleep].

13:33.062 --> 13:35.273
It seems soft.
I'm gonna try it again.

13:35.273 --> 13:39.485
It's not ideal to go back
for a second quench.

13:39.485 --> 13:43.906
<i>It can cause problems</i>
<i>that could end my day.</i>

13:43.906 --> 13:45.825
<i>- The actual shape of the tool</i>
<i>was coming out like</i>

13:45.825 --> 13:49.912
I planned it,
and I'm happy about that.

13:49.912 --> 13:53.291
- John has just quenched that
massive piece of steel.

13:53.291 --> 13:56.252
- Watch the fireball
when he pulls that bad boy out.

13:56.252 --> 13:57.962
all: Oh!

13:57.962 --> 14:00.590
- That was a mustache trimmer.
- Woof.

14:00.590 --> 14:01.966
<i>Whoops, there goes</i>
<i>the mustache.</i>

14:01.966 --> 14:04.343
[laughs]

14:04.343 --> 14:07.555
I got a hardened edge, but the
mass of the thing is so much

14:07.555 --> 14:09.557
<i>that the whole thing is hot.</i>

14:09.557 --> 14:11.517
I can't hold it in my hands.
I need to cool it off.

14:11.517 --> 14:14.687
It's a lot of metal to cool.

14:14.687 --> 14:16.773
all: Oh!

14:16.773 --> 14:18.608
- Oh, [bleep].

14:18.608 --> 14:21.110
- John has just lost his steel
all the way down

14:21.110 --> 14:23.196
in the bottom of that barrel.

14:23.196 --> 14:26.240
The child of Loch Ness
is living in that swamp water.

14:26.240 --> 14:27.492
- Oh, no.

14:27.492 --> 14:30.036
- Here we go.

14:30.036 --> 14:32.038
- Oh!
- Dunking for axe heads.

14:32.038 --> 14:34.082
<i>- This water barrel is gross.</i>

14:34.082 --> 14:35.833
I don't know what all
they've been sticking in there,

14:35.833 --> 14:39.045
<i>but there's scummy,</i>
<i>floaty things in it.</i>

14:39.045 --> 14:41.255
- There is no shower
in the world strong enough

14:41.255 --> 14:43.466
for what he's been doing.

14:43.466 --> 14:46.719
- Ten, nine, eight,

14:46.719 --> 14:50.640
seven, six,
five, four,

14:50.640 --> 14:53.851
three, two, one.

14:53.851 --> 14:56.729
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines. Drop your tools.

14:56.729 --> 14:59.315
This first round
of competition is over.

14:59.315 --> 15:01.234
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:01.234 --> 15:05.071
- Whew, man, that was work,

15:05.071 --> 15:08.616
<i>but I feel good that</i>
<i>I actually got a blade forged.</i>

15:08.616 --> 15:10.701
<i>Kind of half close your eyes,</i>
<i>it's kind of pretty,</i>

15:10.701 --> 15:14.997
but if you look close,
it's pretty damn ugly.

15:14.997 --> 15:17.291
- Bladesmiths, in this first
round of competition,

15:17.291 --> 15:20.670
you were to forge
a multipurpose blade.

15:20.670 --> 15:22.255
Now it's time for the judges
to take a closer

15:22.255 --> 15:23.840
look at your work.

15:23.840 --> 15:25.925
Mark, you're up first.

15:25.925 --> 15:28.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:28.136 --> 15:30.138
<i>- I like your design here.</i>

15:30.138 --> 15:32.348
I like the fact that you have
the hammerhead out here.

15:32.348 --> 15:35.810
<i>You do have a bit of an offset</i>
<i>on your teeth,</i>

15:35.810 --> 15:38.271
and
that's a little narrow there.

15:38.271 --> 15:41.691
So that's something you might
want to address if you move on.

15:41.691 --> 15:44.402
- Nicholas, please present
your blade to the judges.

15:44.402 --> 15:46.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.654 --> 15:48.990
- I think you did a lot
of really nice forge work here,

15:48.990 --> 15:51.242
but your fork's very lean,

15:51.242 --> 15:53.035
right on the edge
of being questionable

15:53.035 --> 15:54.579
if that's gonna hold up

15:54.579 --> 15:56.581
if we get
a lot of pressure on that.

15:56.581 --> 15:57.707
- I hope you've got a plan
for the handle,

15:57.707 --> 15:59.292
because this is really lean.

15:59.292 --> 16:01.502
Your hammerhead
came out very nice,

16:01.502 --> 16:03.171
although it's gonna be
kind of awkward

16:03.171 --> 16:05.631
hammering a nail like that.

16:05.631 --> 16:07.383
- John, you're up.

16:07.383 --> 16:09.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:09.302 --> 16:11.679
<i>- Amazing the fact that</i>
<i>you took all that steel</i>

16:11.679 --> 16:13.306
and moved it the way
that you did.

16:13.306 --> 16:15.183
That was really impressive.

16:15.183 --> 16:16.517
I would have liked
to have seen you

16:16.517 --> 16:19.604
cut that mallet head in half.

16:19.604 --> 16:23.774
- You, sir, are a beast,
and you created a beast,

16:23.774 --> 16:26.611
but a beast
needs to be controlled.

16:26.611 --> 16:28.654
There's so much weight;
there's just a lot of work

16:28.654 --> 16:30.448
that you have to do
to get it there.

16:30.448 --> 16:32.491
This is too big to be

16:32.491 --> 16:35.203
truly something
that I could control myself.

16:35.203 --> 16:37.455
- Garrin, you're up.

16:37.455 --> 16:38.956
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:38.956 --> 16:41.083
<i>- I like what you did.</i>

16:41.083 --> 16:43.628
<i>Again, having the hammerhead</i>
<i>on the bottom end</i>

16:43.628 --> 16:46.672
makes it a little awkward.
It's a long handle.

16:46.672 --> 16:48.174
I'd like to see
some kind of contouring

16:48.174 --> 16:50.426
to make that an easier grip.

16:50.426 --> 16:52.428
- It looks like you left
enough material here.

16:52.428 --> 16:55.932
I worry a little bit that
it gets very lean right here,

16:55.932 --> 16:57.975
<i>right where that junction is.</i>

16:57.975 --> 17:00.353
<i>Once you're prying up,</i>
<i>that's gonna make that tine</i>

17:00.353 --> 17:04.148
a little bit less
sturdy than that.

17:04.148 --> 17:06.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:06.275 --> 17:07.818
- Bladesmiths, the judges'
deliberation is complete,

17:07.818 --> 17:09.737
and they've made
their final decision.

17:09.737 --> 17:11.989
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

17:11.989 --> 17:15.284
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:15.284 --> 17:16.827
John.

17:16.827 --> 17:19.163
Your blade did not
make the cut.

17:19.163 --> 17:22.375
- John, you came up with
a really interesting design,

17:22.375 --> 17:24.210
and you showed us
an amazing amount of skill

17:24.210 --> 17:26.003
moving that steel,

17:26.003 --> 17:28.464
but that extreme weight
has made that a tool

17:28.464 --> 17:30.508
<i>that's just too hard to use,</i>

17:30.508 --> 17:32.843
and that's why
we're letting you go.

17:32.843 --> 17:35.471
- John, please
surrender your blade.

17:35.471 --> 17:36.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:36.889 --> 17:39.058
<i>- Well, it wasn't unexpected.</i>

17:39.058 --> 17:41.018
I just had a massive weapon

17:41.018 --> 17:43.187
<i>that needed massive</i>
<i>amount of work.</i>

17:43.187 --> 17:45.231
I've been forging for 45 years,

17:45.231 --> 17:47.108
<i>and I'm not gonna stop forging</i>

17:47.108 --> 17:49.652
just because I didn't
win a competition.

17:49.652 --> 17:54.448
<i>That's rather silly</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

17:54.448 --> 17:56.659
- Well, bladesmiths, you made
it to the second round,

17:56.659 --> 17:58.369
but that doesn't mean
that anything's gonna get

17:58.369 --> 18:00.162
any easier.

18:00.162 --> 18:01.872
Now that
your blades have been tempered,

18:01.872 --> 18:03.749
it's time to turn them
into fully functional,

18:03.749 --> 18:07.336
multipurpose blades
by attaching handles to them.

18:07.336 --> 18:10.423
You'll have three hours
in which to complete your work.

18:10.423 --> 18:12.425
Make good use of
that time, gentlemen,

18:12.425 --> 18:14.510
because when the time runs out,

18:14.510 --> 18:16.220
your weapons will be tested
for strength and durability

18:16.220 --> 18:18.514
in a pry and hammerhead chop

18:18.514 --> 18:21.726
and for edge retention
in a fire hose slice.

18:21.726 --> 18:25.021
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

18:25.021 --> 18:26.731
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:26.731 --> 18:28.691
Who's in the best position
right now?

18:28.691 --> 18:30.526
- Oh, Mark, as far as
I'm concerned, design-wise.

18:30.526 --> 18:32.653
He can actually use
the hammerhead

18:32.653 --> 18:35.239
like a hammer
with leverage and a handle.

18:35.239 --> 18:36.824
He can get some momentum going.

18:36.824 --> 18:38.576
<i>- Going into round 2,</i>

18:38.576 --> 18:41.245
I'm feeling confident
I can be successful.

18:41.245 --> 18:42.872
<i>The first thing I need to do</i>

18:42.872 --> 18:46.542
is address the issue
of the pry bar.

18:46.542 --> 18:49.587
<i>I want to sculpt it</i>
<i>a little bit so it flares out.</i>

18:49.587 --> 18:52.840
It'll be easier for a nail
to slide up in there

18:52.840 --> 18:54.675
<i>and gives you</i>
<i>something to grab</i>

18:54.675 --> 18:57.887
<i>when you're prying on it.</i>

18:57.887 --> 19:00.056
- The biggest thing that I have
to address right away

19:00.056 --> 19:02.516
is the ergonomics
of the handle.

19:02.516 --> 19:04.310
- What I'd like to see Garrin

19:04.310 --> 19:07.730
do is a smaller variation
of the Yatagan handle,

19:07.730 --> 19:09.482
where it's got flare
at the bottom,

19:09.482 --> 19:11.901
so your hand isn't sliding
under that hammerhead.

19:11.901 --> 19:13.986
- I decide I'm just gonna add
a little swoop

19:13.986 --> 19:16.447
to the end of the handle
of mild steel.

19:16.447 --> 19:17.865
<i>And it should limit the</i>
<i>ability to go off</i>

19:17.865 --> 19:20.076
<i>the end of it.</i>

19:20.076 --> 19:22.244
<i>- One of my biggest concerns</i>
<i>going into round 2</i>

19:22.244 --> 19:25.081
is that the judges pointed out
that my tang is kind of lean,

19:25.081 --> 19:26.624
<i>so I'm really gonna focus on</i>

19:26.624 --> 19:28.417
trying to get that
a little wider,

19:28.417 --> 19:29.794
make it a bit
more user-friendly.

19:29.794 --> 19:32.129
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:32.129 --> 19:34.131
- Nicholas took that
square tubing

19:34.131 --> 19:36.050
and cut a scrap off of it,

19:36.050 --> 19:37.968
and he's welded that on
to the bottom of his tang,

19:37.968 --> 19:39.887
so he's gonna have
some kind of flair

19:39.887 --> 19:41.889
- Smart work.

19:41.889 --> 19:43.474
- I know how to move metal
and put it where I want it.

19:43.474 --> 19:44.725
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:44.725 --> 19:47.478
- 60 minutes has elapsed.

19:47.478 --> 19:50.189
<i>- For my handle I'm going</i>
<i>with a piece of wood.</i>

19:50.189 --> 19:52.733
I'm gonna construct
just a three-piece handle,

19:52.733 --> 19:54.443
<i>slab on both sides,</i>

19:54.443 --> 19:59.198
some pins to hold it
together with the epoxy.

19:59.198 --> 20:01.033
- [laughs] He's gonna glue
his hand to it.

20:01.033 --> 20:02.493
- I'm gonna have to have
to hold

20:02.493 --> 20:05.371
onto his wrist
to test the knife.

20:05.371 --> 20:08.290
<i>- I should have taken a second</i>
<i>to putting some gloves on,</i>

20:08.290 --> 20:10.626
so I didn't get as
much epoxy on myself,

20:10.626 --> 20:13.629
<i>but that's part of</i>
<i>the process sometimes.</i>

20:13.629 --> 20:15.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:15.464 --> 20:16.924
- I'm kind of going back
and forth on what to do

20:16.924 --> 20:18.968
with the pry end
because I don't know

20:18.968 --> 20:22.096
<i>if I want a pry bar to be</i>
<i>as hard as my knife blade.</i>

20:22.096 --> 20:24.265
It just needs to be strong,

20:24.265 --> 20:28.185
<i>so I decide to draw the</i>
<i>temper out of those fore pins.</i>

20:28.185 --> 20:30.438
In other words,
make them softer so that

20:30.438 --> 20:33.107
<i>if there is some kind of</i>
<i>failure in the nail pry,</i>

20:33.107 --> 20:36.402
<i>instead of breaking, I'm gonna</i>
<i>have them bend a little bit.</i>

20:36.402 --> 20:38.154
I hope it doesn't bite me
in the ass.

20:38.154 --> 20:40.948
- Does it compromise
the structural integrity

20:40.948 --> 20:42.491
of the blade itself though?

20:42.491 --> 20:45.369
- Oh, yes.

20:45.369 --> 20:48.414
- I choose a pretty hefty
piece of black micarta,

20:48.414 --> 20:50.040
and I decide that I'm gonna go

20:50.040 --> 20:52.126
with some
stainless-steel Corby bolts

20:52.126 --> 20:54.754
<i>for a solid purchase</i>
<i>on my handle material.</i>

20:57.131 --> 20:59.341
- I'm trying to figure out
what Nicholas is doing.

20:59.341 --> 21:00.926
- He's trying to get
those Corbies

21:00.926 --> 21:03.179
set deep enough
into that material.

21:03.179 --> 21:05.055
<i>- I'm having some problems</i>
<i>with the alignment</i>

21:05.055 --> 21:07.099
<i>and the fit of the Corby bolts.</i>

21:07.099 --> 21:09.643
I'm trying not to panic
at this point,

21:09.643 --> 21:11.771
but I don't have a heck
of a lot of time.

21:11.771 --> 21:13.355
- It looks like the hole
that's drilled

21:13.355 --> 21:15.483
all the way through
isn't wide enough.

21:15.483 --> 21:18.360
- He actually got
his Corby bolts stuck.

21:18.360 --> 21:20.237
<i>- This is bad.</i>

21:20.237 --> 21:21.739
<i>I am wasting</i>
<i>a tremendous amount of time</i>

21:21.739 --> 21:23.491
<i>messing with these bolts.</i>

21:23.491 --> 21:25.868
The clock is ticking down.

21:25.868 --> 21:27.161
<i>It's not looking good.</i>

21:27.161 --> 21:28.829
<i>I think I'm going home.</i>

21:28.829 --> 21:29.598
- Oh, boy.

21:34.835 --> 21:36.754
<i>and the fit of the Corby bolts.</i>

21:36.754 --> 21:38.756
This is bad.

21:38.756 --> 21:40.633
- It looks like the hole
he drilled all the way through

21:40.633 --> 21:42.218
isn't wide enough.

21:42.218 --> 21:44.345
- He actually got
his Corby bolts stuck.

21:44.345 --> 21:46.430
<i>- I jammed one of the bolts</i>
<i>down further</i>

21:46.430 --> 21:48.307
and it finally engages,

21:48.307 --> 21:50.059
<i>but, man,</i>
<i>I've got some big, ugly gaps.</i>

21:50.059 --> 21:52.186
I am wasting
a tremendous amount of time

21:52.186 --> 21:53.479
messing with these bolts.

21:53.479 --> 21:55.272
<i>The clock is ticking down.</i>

21:55.272 --> 21:56.148
<i>I haven't sharpened</i>
<i>my knife yet.</i>

21:56.148 --> 21:58.859
<i>I have to move on.</i>

21:58.859 --> 22:01.195
- 30 minutes.

22:01.195 --> 22:05.032
- I feel good about the contour
that I have for my handle,

22:05.032 --> 22:09.578
so I want the blade to have
a nice convex grind to it,

22:09.578 --> 22:11.539
so it will cut and chop.

22:11.539 --> 22:13.791
- Mark's really just moving
along, man.

22:13.791 --> 22:16.836
- Oh, yeah.
- He could be done early.

22:16.836 --> 22:19.880
<i>- I'm feeling good and</i>
<i>confident as to where I'm at.</i>

22:19.880 --> 22:22.842
Wishing I had a lounge chair
at this point.

22:22.842 --> 22:27.012
<i>- My next priority is to get</i>
<i>my handle finished,</i>

22:27.012 --> 22:31.350
I decide I'm going
to use cocobolo and orange G10

22:31.350 --> 22:33.102
as a liner.

22:33.102 --> 22:36.063
<i>Liners are not</i>
<i>necessary at all,</i>

22:36.063 --> 22:38.607
but I want every single
little bit of advantage

22:38.607 --> 22:40.693
I can get out
of this competition,

22:40.693 --> 22:43.487
<i>and if having a really</i>
<i>nice line between the handle</i>

22:43.487 --> 22:45.656
and the blade
puts me over that edge,

22:45.656 --> 22:47.199
<i>I'm gonna take that chance.</i>

22:47.199 --> 22:49.535
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:49.535 --> 22:52.997
<i>- With only ten minutes left,</i>
<i>I am feeling very nervous.</i>

22:52.997 --> 22:54.999
<i>I haven't even started</i>
<i>to sharpening my knife yet.</i>

22:54.999 --> 22:57.084
I'm really starting to sweat.

22:57.084 --> 22:59.670
- Nicholas did a lot of work
trying to fit his Corby bolts.

22:59.670 --> 23:02.423
So that took a lot of work
and a lot of rime.

23:02.423 --> 23:04.967
- I don't have a lot of time
left, so I take off my belt,

23:04.967 --> 23:06.844
<i>and I clamp it in the vise,</i>

23:06.844 --> 23:08.554
<i>and I start using that</i>
<i>to strop the edge.</i>

23:08.554 --> 23:10.431
- I think that belt's been used
to strop before.

23:10.431 --> 23:11.891
- Yeah, it looks like
it has been.

23:11.891 --> 23:13.976
- [laughs]

23:13.976 --> 23:19.148
Five, four, three, two, one.

23:19.148 --> 23:21.775
Bladesmiths, stop your work.
Drop your tools.

23:21.775 --> 23:23.527
This second round
of competition has ended.

23:23.527 --> 23:25.279
Good job.

23:25.279 --> 23:26.530
<i>- I am happy with my blade.</i>

23:26.530 --> 23:28.574
I have seen J. test blades.

23:28.574 --> 23:30.868
<i>I guess I can say</i>
